Import Files

  • Data was scraped from [https://www.basketball-reference.com/] using Python and .csv files were saved
  • Columns: blank columns need to be removed, columns containing ‘%’ need to be renamed to ‘PCT’, columns containing ‘2’ or ‘3’ will be renamed to include ‘Two’ and ‘Thr’, and periods will be replaced by underscores

Per 100 possessions

  • G, GS, MP, FG_PCT, ThrP_PCT, FT_PCT are not per 100 possessions, they are season totals
per_poss <- read_csv("per_poss.csv")
colnames(per_poss)
##  [1] "Rk"          "Player"      "Pos"         "Age"         "Tm"         
##  [6] "G"           "GS"          "MP"          "FG"          "FGA"        
## [11] "FG PCT"      "3P"          "3PA"         "3P PCT"      "2P"         
## [16] "2PA"         "2P PCT"      "FT"          "FTA"         "FT PCT"

per_poss1 <- subset(per_poss) %>%
  select('Year', everything()) %>%
  select(-c(contains('Unnamed'))) %>%
  rename_at(vars(contains("%")),funs(str_replace_all(., "%","_PCT"))) %>%
  rename_at(vars(contains("3")),funs(str_replace(., "3","Thr"))) %>%
  rename_at(vars(contains("2")),funs(str_replace(., "2","Two"))) %>%
  rename_at(vars(contains(" ")),funs(str_replace_all(., " ","_")))

Exploratory Data Analysis

There’s a fair amount players that we need to remove from teh dataset given their lack of contribution to the team (Ex. playing only a few games or not playing a lot of minutes).

The data includes a team name called ‘TOT’ which indicates that a player played or more than one team. These players’ stats appear on multiple lines - one for each team and one for the Total that season. We need to remove the underlying teams for each player with ‘TOT’ as their team so we’re left with only one row for each player for each season they played. We’ll create a unique index (since the index wasn’t included on the scrape) based on rank (which is essentially an index value based on player name), player name and year. We’ll arrange by Games (TOT will always be the highest) and remove duplicate instances for each dataframe

Per 100 Possesisons

per_poss2 <- per_poss1
per_poss2$player_year <- paste(per_poss1$Rk,per_poss1$Player, per_poss1$Year) # create concatenation

per_poss3 <- per_poss2 %>%

Combined Dataframe

Each of the dataframes are sorted the same way for ease of processing

per_poss3 <- per_poss3 %>% 
  arrange(Year, Player, desc(G))

adv3 <- adv3 %>% 
  arrange(Year, Player, desc(G))

shoot3 <- shoot3 %>% 
  arrange(Year, Player, desc(G))

per_game3 <- per_game3 %>% 
  arrange(Year, Player, desc(G))

There are duplicate columns that will need to be removed before we join the tables

per_poss4 <- per_poss3
adv4 <- adv3
shoot4 <- shoot3
per_game4 <- per_game3

Year, Rank, Player, Pos, Age, TM, and G are all present in each dataframe, so those will be removed. A suffix will be adding to each column name so that we can determine where the stat was initially located

colnames(per_poss4)[8:32] <- paste(colnames(per_poss4)[8:32],"pp",sep="_")

dupcol_df <- per_poss4 %>%
  select(1:33) %>%

dupcol_df <- dupcol_df %>% select(order(colnames(dupcol_df)))
Obvious Duplicated Columns

Columns will be removed based on a hierarchy of the dataframes: 1) Per 100, 2) Advanced, 3) Shooting, 4) Per Game

  • FG_PCT: Per 100, Shooting, and Per Game
  • FT_PCT: Per 100, Per Game
  • G: Per 100, Advanced, Shooting, Per Game
  • GS: Per 100, Per Game
  • MP: Per 100, Advanced, Shooting
  • ThrP_PCT: Per 100, Per Game
  • TwoP_PCT: Per 100, Per Game
dupcol_df1 <- per_poss4 %>%
  select(1,3:33) %>% #remove rank as it's meaningless
  left_join(select(adv4, c(9:29)), by = 'player_year') %>% #remove G and MP
  left_join(select(shoot4, c(10:31)), by = 'player_year') %>% #remove G MP FG_PCT
  left_join(select(per_game4, -c(1:8,12,15,22)), by = 'player_year') #remove FG_PCT, FT_PCT, G, GS, ThrP_PCT, TwoP_PCT

Not so Obvious Duplicated Columns

These columns are named differently, but they account for the same statistics when their values are for each player are reviewed

  • ThrPAr_adv and PCT_FGA_Dis_3P_sho
  • ThrP_PCT_pp and FG_PCT_Dis_3P_sho
  • TwoP_PCT_pp, FG_PCT_Dis_2P_sho,and TwoP_PCT_pg
  • STL_pp and STL_PCT_adv

These duplicated columns will be removed leaving us another step closer to our final dataset

final_df5 <- final_df_qs_mpg_removed %>% replace(is.na(.), 0)

Some of the player names include an asterisk. This asterisk will be removed and a new feature will be engineered called HOF (Hall of Fame), which is a binary column indicating that

final_df5$HOF <- ifelse(grepl("\\*", final_df5$Player),1,0)

final_df5 <- final_df5 %>%
  mutate(Player =gsub("\\*", "", Player))

Some of the player names included foreign letters. The code below removes those letters. Additionally, periods, dashes, and single quotes were removed.

final_df5$Player <- stri_trans_general(final_df5$Player, "Latin-ASCII")

final_df5 <- final_df5 %>%
  mutate(Player =gsub("\\.", "", Player)) %>%
  mutate(Player =gsub("\\-", "", Player)) %>%
  mutate(Player =gsub("\\'", "", Player))

A unique player index was created in excel, imported, and joined to the df. The previous column that was used to remove players with more than one line per season (Tm == ‘Tot’) wasn’t useful for identifying unique players overall.

Only valuable columns for our model were selected, columns were reordered, and a few columns were renamed.

PlayerIndex <- read_excel("PlayerIndex.xlsx")

PCA helped us analyze the data in a lower dimensional space, but we want to try a different clustering method

K-Means

For k-means to run, we need to determine the number of clusters for the algorithm.

set.seed(123) # set seed to ensure reproduceability 
MAX_K <- 20 # max number of clusters
sse <- c() # vector to hold SSE of each model

for (k in 1:MAX_K) {
  algo_k <- kmeans(model_data_norm, centers=k, nstart=25, iter.max=20,algorithm="MacQueen") # k-means algorithm
  sse <- c(sse, algo_k$tot.withinss) # get SSE
}

Generally, where the plot levels off or wherever there’s an elbow is a good way to find the optimal number of clusters.

tibble(k = 1:MAX_K, SSE = sse) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=k, y=SSE)) + 
  geom_point(color="#F84C1E") + geom_line(color="#232D4B") + 
  labs(x = "K", y = "SSE", title = "Where does this level off?") + 
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(1, MAX_K, 1)) + 
  theme_minimal() + #theme_stern() +
  theme(panel.grid.minor.x = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor.y = element_blank())

The plot below doesn’t really show either, so we plot can look at the difference between total within cluster distance for k and k+1

tibble(k = 1:MAX_K, SSE_difference = sse-lead(sse)) %>%
  dplyr::filter(k<MAX_K) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=k, y=SSE_difference)) + 
  geom_point(color="#F84C1E") + geom_line(color="#232D4B") + 
  labs(x = "K", y = "SSE Rolling Difference", title = "A Clearer Picture") + 
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(1, MAX_K, 1)) + 
  theme_minimal() + theme_stern() +
  theme(panel.grid.minor.x = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor.y = element_blank())

This looks to be between 7 or 10, but if we run with a two unit rolling distance, it might give us an even better picture

tibble(k = 1:MAX_K, SSE_difference = sse-2*lead(sse)+lead(sse, 2)) %>%
  dplyr::filter(k<MAX_K-1) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=k, y=SSE_difference)) + 
  geom_point(color="#F84C1E") + geom_line(color="#232D4B") + 
  labs(x = "K", y = "SSE Rolling 2-Unit Difference", title = "An Even Clearer Picture") + 
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(1, MAX_K, 1)) + 
  theme_minimal() + #theme_stern() + 
  theme(panel.grid.minor.x = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor.y = element_blank())

Here it’s pretty clear that 7 is about where the data levels off, so we will use that for our clustering algo

colnames(model_data_norm) <- gsub(x = colnames(model_data_norm), pattern = "\\.", replacement = "%") # make sure columns are named correctly
K <- 7
kmeans8 <- kmeans(model_data_norm, centers=K, nstart=25, iter.max=20)
km_centers <- data.frame(kmeans8$centers) # SCALED cluster centers/means
model_data_clusters <- data.frame(Cluster = kmeans8$cluster, model_data_norm)

# name clusters before pivoting
km_centers$Cluster <- c('Cluster 1', 'Cluster 2', 'Cluster 3',
                        'Cluster 4', 'Cluster 5', 'Cluster 6',
                        'Cluster 7')

km_centers <- km_centers %>%
  pivot_longer(!Cluster, names_to = 'feature', values_to = 'z_val') # pivot data to make plotting easier
colnames(km_centers) <- gsub(x = colnames(km_centers), pattern = "\\.", replacement = "%")

# reset the order of predictor variables for plotting
km_centers$feature <- factor(km_centers$feature) 

# reset the order of clusters for plotting (cluster 10 would default to come after cluster 1 and before cluster 2)
km_centers$Cluster <- factor(km_centers$Cluster, levels=c('Cluster 1', 'Cluster 2', 'Cluster 3',
                                                          'Cluster 4', 'Cluster 5', 'Cluster 6',
                                                          'Cluster 7'))

After clustering was done, we were left with seven new player types: 1. Well-Rounded Bigs 2. Physical Bigs 3. Game Generals 4. Game Lieutenants 5. Shot-Creating Sharpshooters 6. MVP Bigs 7. Three-Point Threats

Below is a plot of one of the clusters. The dark dot indicates where that cluster ranks compared to the other clusters for each stat. The dotted lines act as a partition to differentiate between the categories of statistics

If we look towards the right of the graph, we’ll see that the players in this cluster rank towards the bottom of the ThrP (three point) shooting categories. They’re at the top in FGA_d2p (Field goal attempts that were two-point shots), which is inline with them ranking last in most three-point shooting categories. They’re also towards the top in a lot of the rebounding categories. A more deatiled description is included below.

Historical and Current Cluster Analysis

The below plot shows how the player types have evolved since the 2000-2001 season and a brief summary of each cluster is included.

  • Well-Rounded Bigs have had their ups and downs, ranging from 9.3% to 19% of players in the league, however it’s not that different today than it is from 2001.
  • Physical Bigs have steadily decreased and the position appears close to becoming obsolete. As the style of play has changed, so has the need for this specific player type.
  • Game Generals have more or less remained consistent. This player type has been valued every season.
  • Game Lieutenants have steadily decreased, which is interesting, but it’s likely that Game Lieutenants have transitioned into Three-Point Threats over the years.
  • Shot-Creating Sharpshooters have had equal periods of increase and decrease.
  • MVP Bigs have remained relatively constant, but appear to be phasing out.
  • Three-Point Threats have grown significantly over the date range. It’s a clear indication that 3-point shooters are more common than ever.
ggplot(model_data_clusters1, aes(x=Year, fill=factor(Cluster))) +

  stat_count(geom = "text", 
             aes(label = stat(count)),

  theme(legend.key.height=unit(1, "cm"))

Key takeaways from the teams above .500

  • Phoenix has two Game Generals and two MVP Bigs
  • Chicago and Milwaukee have two Game Generals and one MVP Big
  • Cleveland has two MVP Bigs and one Game General
  • Boston and Brooklyn have two MVP Bigs and no Game Generals
  • Each team has at least a Game General or a MVP Big

Key takeaways from the teams below .500

  • Detroit and Indiana don’t have a Game General or a MVP Big
  • The Lakers (LAL) have two Game Generals and one MVP Big. This team includes Lebron James, Russell Westbrook, and Anthony Davis and were plagued by injuries this past season.
  • All the other teams have at least one Game General and one MVP Big

Game Generals and MVP Bigs are by far the most valuable. If we look at the player type history of current Game Generals and MVP Bigs, we see that many of these players developed into this position, rather than always being in this position.

The current Game Generals in the league (30, on the right). The x-axis indicates the year and the bars indicate the count of historical player types for each current Game Generals. A complete player type history for each player can be found in the appendix. Generally speaking, it would appear that Shot-Creating Sharpshooters transition into Game Generals most often (given the frequency of green). A history of each player’s player type is also included.

good_players_hist3 <- model_data_clusters1 %>%
  filter(Player %in% play_list_3) %>%
  arrange(Player, desc(Year), Cluster) %>%
  group_by(Player) %>% mutate(count=n())

ggplot(data = good_players_hist3, aes(x = Year, fill = factor(Cluster))) +
  geom_bar(position = "fill") + ylab("Proportion by Count") +
  stat_count(geom = "text", 
             aes(label = stat(count)),
             position=position_fill(vjust=0.5), colour="Black") +
  scale_fill_discrete(name = "Player\nType", 
                      labels =c('Game\nLieutenants', 'Shot-Creating\nSharpshooters', 'Well-Rounded\nBigs','Game\nGenerals','MVP Bigs')) +
  theme(legend.key.height=unit(1, "cm"))

good_players_hist3 %>% arrange(Player, desc(Year), Cluster) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Year, y=reorder(Player,count), color = factor(Cluster))) +
  geom_point()

The current MVP Bigs in the league (20, on the right). The x-axis indicates the year and the bars indicate the count of historical player types for each current MVP Bigs.
